PAUL H. O'NEILL

In early 1994, an avalanche of cheap Russian metal threatened to bury
America's world-leading aluminum companies. Aluminum Co. of America's CEO,
60-year-old PAUL H. O'NEILL, pushed for a multinational solution, which
included painful smelter shutdowns in the U.S. He also pressed forward with
global acquisitions, from Italy to Australia. With aluminum prices on the
rebound in 1995 and world supply and demand on a more even keel, Alcoa
motored to strong earnings.

