WILLIAM C. STEERE JR.

For WILLIAM C. STEERE JR., 59-year-old CEO of Pfizer, the big payoff came
in 1995. He sold off nondrug operations and refused to shell out billions
for distributors, as rivals have. Instead, the avid helicopter skier has
focused on riskier new products. Driven by antidepressant Zoloft and
antihypertensive Norvasc, Pfizer's net income in 1995 rose 20%, to nearly
$1.56 billion, while sales gained 23%, to $10.2 billion.

