CONSTITUTIONALITY OF COMPELLING DISCLOSURES CONCERNING MOTION PICTURE
ALTERATIONS

By Henry Cohen, American Law Division.  5 pages.  Although movie
marquees and posters, and video cassette casings and boxes, serve to
identify a film and the individuals associated with it, they also
implicitly propose a commercial transaction.  If the bill required
that a film itself disclose information, a better case could be made
that the bill regulated noncommercial speech.  As it is, however, it
appears more likely that the bill would be viewed as regulating
solely commercial speech.  Order No. 92-256 A.

The full report, as described above and authored by the Congressional
Research Service, costs $47 from Penny Hill Press, 6440 Wiscasset
Road, Bethesda, MD  20816, 301-229-8229.



