COMMAND AND CONTROL:  DEFENSE'S USE OF ENGINEERING
CONTRACTORS FOR ACQUIRING AUTOMATED SYSTEMS

Order No.:  GAO/IMTEC-91-19
Pages:  17

The Department of Defense relies on both in-house and
outside technical expertise to design and develop highly
complex command, control, communications, and intelligence
systems.  This report examines the extent to which DOD uses
engineering support contracts for advice and direction in
acquiring automated data processing systems.  DOD data show
that from fiscal years 1985 through 1989 show that DOD spent
about $3.4 billion for engineering and technical support of
system acquisitions.  Air Force was by far the largest user,
accounting for over $2 billion of the $3.4 billion spent.
DOD'S annual expenditures went from $494.5 million in fiscal
year 1985 to $891.7 million in fiscal year 1989, an 80-
percent increase.

The above-described report is available free from the U.S.
