<HR>
<A NAME = "28"></A>Copyright
FTC:WATCH via NewsNet
January 17, 1996

GM order changed


General Motors has convinced the Federal Trade Commissioners to soften a 1979
order that bars the car maker from placing the name of a car division on an
engine label unless the car division also manufactured the engine (i.e., no
fair identifying Oldsmobiles as having "Rocket 88" engines when the engines
were built by, say, the Chevrolet Division and installed in Chevy's as well).

GM's corporate restructurings since 1979 have resulted in the removal of
engine production from the nameplate divisions that existed then.  This
automotive alchemy constitutes changed conditions of fact, determined the
Commission, allowing it to reopen and modify the order.  Under the modified
order in C-2966, GM can display brand nameplates on engines that are
materially different from those displaying all other brand nameplates, and
cannot display different brand nameplates on identical engines.

REFERENCE: FTC Press Advisory, December 22




